818181819,"coord_origin":"BOTTOMLEFT"},"charspan":[0,610]}],"orig":"This is an example of how to format tables and figures that span multiple pages. For the first appearance of any table, you should include the table title/number followed by the entire caption. There must be some formatting that separates the title from the caption; you can bold the title, italicize the title, or add punctuation (a period or colon) between the title and caption. You can also bold or italicize the title and use punctuation to clearly separate these two elements. However, you should not bold or italicize the caption, as these are meant to add emphasis and make text more difficult to read.","text":"This is an example of how to format tables and figures that span multiple pages. For the first appearance of any table, you should include the table title/number followed by the entire caption. There must be some formatting that separates the title from the caption; you can bold the title, italicize the title, or add punctuation (a period or colon) between the title and caption. You can also bold or italicize the title and use punctuation to clearly separate these two elements. However, you should not bold or italicize the caption, as these are meant to add emphasis and make text more difficult to read.","formatting":null,"hyperlink":null},{"self_ref":"#/texts/3","parent":{"cref":"#/groups/0"},"children":[],"content_layer":"body","meta":null,"label":"list_item","prov":[{"page_no":1,"bbox":{"l":108.02,"t":498.118,"r":374.71,"b":485.0415820895522,"coord_origin":"BOTTOMLEFT"},"charspan":[0,51]}],"orig":" For example: Table 1. This is an example caption.","text":" For example: Table 1. This is an example caption.","formatting":null,"hyperlink":null,"enumerated":false,"marker":""},{"self_ref":"#/texts/4","parent":{"cref":"#/body"},"children":[],"content_layer":"body","meta":null,"label":"text","prov":[{"page_no":1,"bbox":{"l":90.024,"t":467.73400000000004,"r":524.8040000000001,"b":375.04418181818187,"coord_origin":"BOTTOMLEFT"},"charspan":[0,306]}],"orig":"If a table does not fit on one page or is split into two parts by the page break, you must include the title and full caption before the table starts, as is standard. For any subsequent page on which the table continues, you should include the table title followed by the word ' continued ' in parenthesis.","text":"If a table does not fit on one page or is split into two parts by the page break, you must include the title and full caption before the table starts, as is standard. For any subsequent page on which the table continues, you should include the table title followed by the word ' continued ' in parenthesis.","formatting":null,"hyperlink":null},{"self_ref":"#/texts/5","parent":{"cref":"#/groups/1"},"children":[],"content_layer":"body","meta":null,"label":"list_item","prov":[{"page_no":1,"bbox":{"l":108.02,"t":359.258,"r":540.598,"b":236.20418181818184,"coord_origin":"BOTTOMLEFT"},"charspan":[0,422]}],"orig":" For example, ' Table 1 (continued). ' should appear on any page after the first. Do not include the caption on any page after the first. This line should appear in the same position that the table title and caption do prior to the table ' s appearance on the first page. The spacing between this ' Table 1 (continued). ' title and the table itself should be the exact same as all of your other table titles and captions.","text":" For example, ' Table 1 (continued). ' should appear on any page after the first. Do not include the caption on any page after the first. This line should appear in the same position that the table title and caption do prior to the table ' s appearance on the first page. The spacing between this ' Table 1 (continued). ' title and the table itself should be the exact same as all of your other table titles and captions.","formatting":null,"hyperlink":null,"enumerated":false,"marker":""},{"self_ref":"#/texts/6","parent":{"cref":"#/body"},"children":[],"content_layer":"bo